r:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE015557%2F1"><gtr:id>BCC80AE9-993C-445E-BEE5-6A836A2E39BC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Contesting Social Diversity in the British Armed Forces: Military Doctrine, Society, and the Limits to Identity.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E015557/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>In recent years, the British armed forces have revised a number of key personnel policies. Legislative challenges, demographic shifts and calls for extended rights from within the forces, have led recruiters to look beyond the pool of white, (assumed) heterosexual males that have traditionally filled the military?s ranks. However, it is this traditional pool of recruits who have shaped military traditions and values - deemed necessary to defend Britain - and who continue to dominate the forces statistically and culturally. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>As the sole wielders of state sanctioned violence in defence of Britain and its interests, the military have argued for a ?need to be different? from the society they serve; that social diversity policies must be balanced with maintaining the distinctive values that underpin its ?operational effectiveness?. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Through qualitative interviews and ethnographies with military personnel, this research examines the significance of social diversity, the ?need to be different? and ?operational effectiveness? to the self-identity and relationships of military personnel. By exploring how military personnel negotiate these principles at a micro level of social identity and relationships, it offers insights into previously under-explored challenges to the military?s social diversity goals. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>79761</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F221801A-3358-4E84-9849-C742DB3C53A0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Effecting Discrimination</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Armed Forces &amp; Society</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/3e167301d87b77f81721b0c33df802c1"><gtr:id>3e167301d87b77f81721b0c33df802c1</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Basham V</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa8fa87260a11</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3702EE7A-970A-4E3C-AFFF-E6BD226648B1</gtr:id><gtr:title>Harnessing Social Diversity in the British Armed Forces: The Limitations of 'Management' Approaches</